2. Geological setting clariﬁed the paleophytogeography of Western Gondwana. Haplostigma Seward, 1932, was identiﬁed in several Middle–Late Devonian localities in South America, such as Argentina (Gutie´ rrez, 1996), Bolivia (Di Pasquo et al., 2009), Brazil (Kra¨usel, 1954), and Chile (Moisan et al., 2011). In the Parana´ Basin, this genus was already identiﬁed from a single specimen (Kra¨usel, 1954) found in Ponta Grossa, state of Parana´ . This locality has been destroyed due to urban growth. The present contribution describes plant fossils assigned to the morphogenus Haplostigma, recently recovered from a new locality of the Sa˜o Domingos Formation (eastern Parana´ Basin, Middle Devonian) in the Parana´ , southern Brazil. The other Gondwanan occurrences of the genus are analyzed in order to summarize the stratigraphic distribution and perform a paleophy- togeographic analysis of these Devonian lycopsids. The Parana´ Basin is a polycyclic intracratonic and intercontinental basin on the South-American platform, covering ca. 1,600,000 km2 in southern Brazil and central Uruguay, eastern Paraguay, and northeastern Argentina (Fig. 1). Milani et al. (1998) subdivided the stratigraphic record of this basin into six second-order depositional supersequences, ranging from the Late Ordovician up to the Late

The Devonian rocks of the Parana´ Basin are represented by two sedimentary depositional centers: the northern Alto Garc¸as and the southern Apucarana Sub-basins. Grahn et al. (2013) subdivided the Devonian of the Apucarana Sub-basin into three formations (in ascending order): the Furnas, Ponta Grossa, and Sa˜o Domingos formations, and revised the stratigraphic sequence scheme proposed by Bergamaschi and Pereira (2001). The lithology of the Sa˜o Domingos Formation is predominantly composed of sandtones interbedded with argillaceous shale with asphalt (as high-TOC claystone). In the basal part, poorly sorted conglomeratic sandstones occur, followed upward by shale and micaceous siltstone rich in plant debris. The unit was interpreted as a marine continental shelf environment of early late Emsian to late early Frasnian age (Grahn et al., 2013). 3. Material and methods The paleontological material was collected from the Sa˜o Domingos Formation at the upper part of the Ita´ ytyba outcrop (11–12 m), in Tibagi Municipality, Parana´ , southern Brazil (Fig. 1). The locality is positioned in the topmost part of the Tibagi- Ventania section (Horodyski et al., 2012; Matsumura et al., 2013), showing an exposure 16 m thick. In association with land plants remains (Haplostigma sp., Palaeostigma sp., Spongiophyton sp. and undetermined plant debris), several ichnofossils (vertical and horizontal structures) and a few marine invertebrates (brachio- pods and trilobites) are preserved (Fig. 2). The paleontological material is housed at the laboratory of Stratigraphy and Paleontology of the Department de Geosciences (DEGEO), in the State University of Ponta Grossa, and labeled as DEGEO/MP. The specimens are preserved as impressions, adpres- sions, casts and molds, some of them composed of parts and counter-parts (sensu Schopf, 1975). The study followed the pattern methodology used in paleobotany, including the de´gagement technique (Leclercq, 1960) using ﬁne steel needles, observations with a stereomicroscope, and measurements with a pachymeter and ruler. Photographs were taken with a Nikon D90 and 105 mm macro lens. The fragmentary state of terrestrial Early Paleozoic fossil plants often hinders reliable identiﬁcation (Edwards, 1982; Bonamo et al., 1988). Although fertile structures are commonly required in species delimitation, vegetative structures may also provide a good source of information to separate different taxa. In herbaceous lycopsids, leaves may be the only structure distinguishing two genera (Bonamo et al., 1988; Berry and Edwards, 1995). Unfortunately, leaves are frequently very difﬁcult to see or are poorly and partially preserved, if present, in Haplostigma-type material. Therefore, the stem and leaf cushions were analyzed in detail in order to assess different morphospecies, comparing with other Devonian lycopsids from the literature (Grierson and Banks, 1963, 1983; Fairon-Demaret, 1972, 1980; Edwards and Benedetto, 1985; Bonamo et al., 1988; Berry and Edwards, 1995, 1996a, 1997; Gutie´ rrez, 1996; Gutie´ rrez and Archangelsky, 1997; Carrizo and Azcuy, 2006). According to Benca et al. (2014), morphometric techniques can provide useful diagnostic information for frag- mentary fossil axes of early land plants, even in the absence of reproductive structures. The following characteristics previously used by different authors (Meyen, 1976; Thomas and Meyen, 1984; Gutie´ rrez, 1996; Gutie´ rrez and Archangelsky, 1997; Cariglino et al., 2012) were selected (Figs. 3 and 4):

Systematic paleobotany Class LYCOPSIDA Scott, 1909 Genus Haplostigma Seward, 1932 399 Type-species: Haplostigma irregularis (Schwarz) Seward, 1932. Remarks: The morphogenus Haplostigma was originally proposed to describe the stem impressions occuring from Middle to Upper Devonian sequences in South Africa (Upper Bokkeveld and Lower Witteberg groups), from the new species H. irregularis. Haplostigma comprises herbaceous lycopsid stems, probably forked, bearing rounded to oval leaf cushions in a helical arrangement, and rigid spine-like appendages (Seward, 1932). Kra¨usel and Dolianiti (1957) noted that the fossil material used by Seward (1932) probably belonged to more than one genus. Thus, some of the specimens illustrated by Seward (1932: p. 360, pl. XXIII, ﬁgs. 1, 3, 4; pl. XXIV, ﬁgs. 8, 9, 12; text-ﬁg. 1) were transferred to Palaeostigma Kra¨ usel and Dolianiti, 1957. In South Africa, Plumstead (1967) separated other specimens that were formerly included in H. irregularis, and described them as Drepanophycus – now H. kowiensis (Plumstead) Anderson and Anderson, 1985. Ad- ditionally, due to the commonly fragmented and defoliated (leaﬂess) state (and also the lack of reproductive structures) of Haplostigma stems, several authors (e.g., McLoughlin and Long, 1994; Gutie´ rrez, 1996; Gutie´ rrez and Archangelsky, 1997; Cingolani et al., 2002; Moisan et al., 2011) differentiated this

Table 1 summarizes some of the main characteristics of a number of Devonian herbaceous lycopod genera. According to these morphological characteristics, Haplostigma clearly differs from Drepanophycus Go¨ ppert, 1852, which includes stems that are dichotomously branched, with robust axes and persistent falcate leaves inserted on larger leaf bases (Banks and Grierson, 1968; Fairon-Demaret, 1978). Thus, the wider stem and the slender and non-persistent leaves of Haplostigma are the main features that differentiate the two genera. Haplostigma differs from Malanzania Archangelsky, Azcuy et Wagner, 1981, in having larger leaf cushions, loosely distributed on the stem, and longitudinally arranged and separated by ridges in most cases. A few specimens included in Haplostigma show preserved leaf bases, while in Malanzania the leaves are unknown (Archangelsky et al., 1981; Archangelsky, 1983). Haplostigma differs from Archaeosigillaria Kidston emend. Berry and Edwards (1997), in having wider stems, enlarged leaf cushions forming broadly rounded to sub-hexagonal patterns delimited by narrow grooves, and slender and non-persistent leaves. The leaf morphology is unknown in Archaeosigillaria (Berry and Edwards, 1997). Haplostigma differs from Colpodexylon Banks emend. Berry and Edwards (1995), in having a wider stem, 12–16 leaf cushions in one gyre, and slender and non-persistent leaves. In Colpodexylon, the leaves are persistent, trifurcate in a single plane, with the lateral segments shorter than the central one (Grierson and Banks, 1963; Berry and Edwards, 1995). Haplostigma differs from Haskinsia Grierson et Banks emend. Berry and Edwards (1996), in having a wider stem and slender and non-persistent leaves (Grierson and Banks, 1963, 1983; Edwards and Benedetto, 1985; Bonamo et al., 1988; Berry and Edwards, 1996a). Haplostigma differs from Gilboaphyton Arnold emend. Berry and Edwards (1997), in having a wider stem and slender and non- persistent leaves. In addition, Gilboaphyton has small stems, with enlarged bases forming broadly fusiform to hexagonal patterns delimited by narrow grooves. Persistent leaves divided into a large medial segment and two smaller and shorter, distally directed opposite lateral segments are also present in Gilboaphyton (Berry and Edwards, 1997). Haplostigma differs from Protolepidodendron (Krejci, 1880) Gothan ex Potonie´ , 1921, in having a wider stem, with non- persistent and unbranched leaves. Specimens included in Pro- tolepidodendron show forked leaves (Grierson and Banks, 1963; Fairon-Demaret, 1972, 1980; Jurina, 2009). Finally, Haplostigma differs from Leclercqia Banks, Bonamo et Grierson 1972 emend. Bonamo, Banks et Grierson 1988, emend. Gensel et Kasper 2005, in having wider stems with non-persistent and unbranched leaves. Specimens included in Leclercqia show slender stems bearing three-dimensional leaves with ﬁve or more tips (Bonamo et al., 1988). Based on the above comparisons, all the herbaceous lycopsids studied herein can be assigned to the genus Haplostigma, which features stems up to 20 mm wide and rarely branched dichotomously. Other diagnostic characters are (Table 1): enlarged spine-like leaf cushions forming rounded to sub- hexagonal patterns, arranged in pseudosigillarioid to sigillarioid phyllotaxis; leaf cushions forming well-deﬁned vertical ridges (orthostichies); leaves not persistent, but when present, they are slender and unbranched; reproductive structures unknown. Currently, Haplostigma includes ﬁve morphospecies: H. irregularis, H. furquei Frenguelli, 1952, H. kowiensis Anderson and Anderson, 1985, H. lineare (Walkom) McLoughlin and Long, 1994, and H. baldisii Gutie´ rrez and Archangelsky, 1997. The leaves have been described only for H. furquei (Gutie´ rrez, 1996), H. baldisii (Gutie´ rrez and Archangelsky, 1997), and H. irregularis (present study). All leaf-type appendages are unbranched. In H. furquei, they are slender, up to 7 mm long. H. baldisii leaves are robust, falcate, and slightly ﬂattened along the ad-abaxial axes and with acute apices. H. irregularis bears slender, up to 2 mm long and apparently little persistent leaf-type appendages (Fig. 5(B)). The highly fragmented specimen DEGEO/MP-4622 depicted and reconstituted in Fig. 6 shows a stem bearing leaf cushions departing at divergent angles as high as 508 and 608 each other (black arrows) and separated by a dark organic tissue (white arrow). We have seen more than one hundred Haplostigma stems and this feature is very rare; we suggest it could represent a dichotomously branching area on stem. Although the species H. furquei and H. baldisii were described as unbranched stem (Gutie´ rrez, 1996; Gutie´ rrez and Archangelsky, 1997), this feature has already been illustrated by Plusmtead (1967: pl. XIII, ﬁg. 3).

Leaf cushions are rounded (2 2 mm; MP-7280, MP-7286; Fig. 5(E)) to longitudinally oval (2 3 mm; MP-7111, 7127, 7296; Fig. 5(F)) and form vertically aligned ridges. In lateral view, when the leaf bases are preserved, the leaf cushions show a spine-like projection (1 mm long) on their upper parts (Fig. 5(A, B)). They also are equidistantly separated from adjacent leaf cushions and arranged in pseudosigillarioid phyllotaxis (ıˆ = 458) in which orthostichies and uniform parastichies are well deﬁned (MP- 4976, 7101; Fig. 5(G, J)). Sometimes, the ridges are laterally separated by straight longitudinal (MP-7101; Fig. 5(D)) to slightly sinuous (MP-4960a; Fig. 5(E)) grooves up to 1 mm wide. Usually, 5–7 leaf cushions are present on each half turn of the stem (MP-7101; Fig. 5(G)). When present, the leaf scar is located on the upper part of the leaf cushion, as evidenced by preserved organic matter (MP-7117; Fig. 5(H)). Reproductive structures have not been observed (Table 2). Remarks: These specimens most closely resemble H. irregularis, H. furquei, H. baldisii, H. kowiensis, and H. lineare. They differ from H. furquei, which features pseudosigillarioid phyllotaxy (ıˆ = 25– 358), and a vertical distance between leaf cushions on the same ridge greater than the horizontal distance between alternating ridges. They also differ from H. baldisii, which features sigillarioid phyllotaxy (ıˆ = 35–558), parastichies not deﬁned, 6–9 leaf cushions on each half turn of the stem, vertical distance between leaf cushions on the same ridge less than the horizontal distance between alternating ridges, and more robust and falcate leaves on the ad-abaxial axis. They also differ from H. kowiensis, which features smaller and longitudinally elongated hexagonal leaf cushions. Lastly, they differ from H. lineare, which features elliptical to fusiform leaf cushions with sigillaroid phyllotaxy (ıˆ = 15–308). Based on these differences, the material studied herein can be assigned to H. irregularis, which includes axes of herbaceous lycopsids bearing equidistant leaf cushions (Fig. 5(D, G, K)), arranged in pseudosigillarioid phyllotaxy (ıˆ = 458), and slender non-persistent leaves (Fig. 5(A, B)). Morphospecies of Haplostigma Because of the different degrees and types of preservation (high fragmentation, absence of leaves and reproductive structures) of 407 Haplostigma stems, it is difﬁcult to reconstruct the whole plant. The poor preservation and the paucity of features preserved on stems only allow their separation into different mophospecies. The question of whether all these morphospecies belong to a single natural taxon can be resolved only when more-complete specimens are obtained. Up to now, the statements that these morphospecies are ontogenetic variations or represent different parts of the same plant are merely speculative. Notably, all these morphospecies were found in the same level on the Ita´ ytyba outcrop. This may indicate that these fragments belong to a single

Thus, the chronos- tratigraphic position of sedimentary deposits as well as their correlations remain relatively speculative or imprecise. The stratigraphic position of the fossil plants and marine invertebrates in the Devonian of Gondwana, together with palynological data, requires further study, except perhaps for data from Argentina, Bolivia and Brazil, where a robust framework has been built over the last ten years (Di Pasquo, 2007, 2013; Di Pasquo and Noetinger, 2008; Di Pasquo et al., 2009, 2013; Amena´ bar, 2009; Grahn et al., 2013). Although different fossil groups were used, the main stratigraphic range of occurrence of Haplostigma is well marked within the Eifelian-Givetian interval, as observed by Di Pasquo Gondwana is found in the gray shales of the Pircas Negras Formation, Chinguillos Group, Argentina (Baldis and Sarudiansky, 1975). The authors determined a probable age of (?)Late Emsian, based on the associated trilobite Phacops chavelai. In a younger deposit, Early Eifelian in age, Haplostigma has also been found, in Argentina, in the Pescado (Di Pasquo et al., 2013; Matsumura et al., 2014) and Punta Negra formations (Peralta, 2013). In turn, from the Late Eifelian to the Eifelian/Givetian boundary, Haplostigma has been recorded, in Argentina, in the Los Monos Formation, Tarija Basin (Di Pasquo et al., 2013); in Bolivia, in the Huamapampa Formation, Tarija Basin (Sua´ rez-Riglos, 1975); and in Brazil, in the Sa˜o Domingos Formation, Parana´ Basin (Matsumura et al., 2013, 2014). From the Givetian/Early Frasnian interval to the Famennian, the genus has also been recorded, in Argentina, in the Lo´ len (Cingolani et al., 2002), Chigua´ (Amena´ bar, 2009), and Punta Negra formations (Frenguelli, 1951, 1952; Peralta, 2013); in Bolivia, in the Los Monos and Iquiri formations (Di Pasquo et al., 2013); in Chile, in the El Toco Formation (Moisan et al., 2011); in South Africa, in the Upper Bokkeveld and Lower Witteberg groups (Seward, 1932; Plumstead, 1967); in Antarctica, in the Wilkins Formation (Mildenhall and Schopf, 1980), Beacon Heights Orthoquartzite (Plumstead, 1962), Aztec Siltstone (McLoughlin and Long, 1994), and Dover Sandstone (Schopf, 1968); and in Australia, in the Fiery Range Porphyry (McLoughlin and Long, 1994). Based on these records, Haplostigma apparently ﬁrst appeared (FAD) in the (?)Late Emsian of northwestern Argentina. Beginning with the Eifelian/Givetian interval, this genus became widespread, expanding its geographic distribution throughout Gondwana, occupying several Western Gondwana regions and reaching the other Gondwanan continents at the end of this epoch, except for its absence in the Indian peninsula (Fig. 11). Finally, during the Late Frasnian/Famennian interval, this taxon was recorded only in a few localities in South America (Bolivia and Chile), South Africa (Cape Province), Antarctica (Victoria Land) and Australia (New South Wales), becaming extinct at the end of the Devonian Period. 5.3. Paleophytogeographic signiﬁcance Despite the divergence in South Pole location in Gondwana, as seen in the Devonian paleogeographic maps proposed by Scotese et al. (1999) and Torsvik and Cocks (2011, 2013), both paleogeo- graphic models show that Western Gondwana underwent only slight tectonic movements during the Lochkovian–Frasnian inter- val. Paleobotanical data from the Early to Late Devonian of South America (Edwards and Benedetto, 1985; Berry et al., 2000; Gerrienne et al., 2001; Di Pasquo et al., 2009, 2013; Matsumura et al., 2013, 2014), South Africa (Seward, 1932; Plumstead, 1967; Anderson and Anderson, 1985), Antarctica (Mildenhall and Schopf, 1980; McLoughlin and Long, 1994) and Australia (McLoughlin and Long, 1994; Meyer-Berthaud et al., 2003) support the hypothesis of the existence of a distinct phytogeographic domain, named the
W.M.K. Matsumura et al. / Geobios 48 (2015) 397–415
Gondwanan Realm by Edwards (1990a) (Wnuk, 1996). All these land plant assemblages were located in high latitudes (60–808 S) under a cool-temperate climate (Scotese et al., 1999), as evidenced by cold-water marine invertebrates (Malvinokaffric Realm; Melo, 1988) (Figs. 12, 13). During the Early Devonian, land plants were mainly represen- ted by bryophytes, psilophytes and cooksonioids in South America (Gerrienne et al., 2001; Di Pasquo and Noetinger, 2008; Edwards et al., 2009; Matsumura et al., 2014). From the Middle to early Late Devonian, herbaceous lycopsids became the main elements (Edwards, 1990b). With the advances in research on Western Gondwana ﬂoras, the hypothesis of Gensel (1986) that Pre- Carboniferous ﬂoras were uniform across the globe is no longer supported (Wnuk, 1996; Di Pasquo et al., 2009; Matsumura et al., 2014). Di Pasquo et al. (2009), based on the records and distribution of Haplostigma associated with Grandispora pseudoreticulata and To date, Haplostigma has not been recorded outside of Gondwanan deposits, and could therefore be considered as an endemic element of this continent. This pattern of paleophytogeo- graphic distribution contrasts with those observed for other herbaceous lycopsids (Drepanophycus, Colpodexylon, Haskinsia, Gilboaphyton, Protolepidodendron, and Leclercqia), which have also been recorded in lower to middle paleolatitudes from Laurussia, viz. United States, China, Canada, Germany and Belgium (Banks, 1944, 1960, 1966, Grierson and Banks, 1963, 1983; Bonamo et al., 1988; Edwards and Berry, 1991). 411 other endemic spores, proposed a new subdivision of the Gondwanan Realm in Western Gondwana, termed the Afro- South-American Subrealm (ASA), that would have occurred during the Middle to Late Devonian interval (Eifelian to Frasnian). These authors stressed the need for palynological studies in Haplostigma- bearing deposits in order to check if this co-ocurrence is also valid for other Gondwanan regions. Fig. 12. (Color online.) Continental terrains: F., Falklands; Fl., Florida; La., Laurasia. As observed by Moisan et al. (2011), small to medium-sized, fast-growing herbaceous lycopsids were apparently very success- ful and well adapted to the cool-temperate climate zones at these high latitudes, where the long annual periods of darkness were probably a signiﬁcant limiting factor for the development of land plants, in addition to the low winter temperatures. The only geographic barriers that may have affected the distribution and long-distance dispersal of the herbaceous lycopsid Haplostigma through Gondwana were apparently epeiric seas and uplands (Edwards, 1990a; Di Pasquo et al., 2009; Pfefferkorn et al., 2014). In analyzing the occurrences of Haplostigma during the Late Emsian-Early Givetian interval in Western Gondwana (Figs. 11, 12), one can observe that this taxon was well distributed in high latitudes situated within the cool-temperate climate zone (according to Scotese et al., 1999). However, from the Late Givetian to Early Famennian, Haplostigma extended to lower- latitude regions or terrains (e.g., Antarctic and Australia), reaching the warm-temperate climate zone (Fig. 13). This dispersal from western to Eastern Gondwana may have been triggered by the Famennian glacial event recorded in South America (Loboziak et al., 1995; Melo and Loboziak, 2003; Caputo et al., 2008). This glacial event was likely responsible for hindering or preventing the growth of land plants in most parts of high-latitude terrains. 6. Conclusions The study of plant material preserved in the Ita´ ytyba outcrop of the Sa˜o Domingos Formation, Middle Devonian of the Parana´ Basin, situated at Tibagi, Parana´ State, southern Brazil, indicated that it can be classiﬁed in Haplostigma, a morphogenus of herbaceous lycopsid stems recorded in strata of the Middle to Upper Devonian, mainly in Western Gondwana deposits. The morphology of stems and leaf cushions proved to be identical to those of Haplostigma stems previously recorded in South America (Gutie´ rrez, 1996;
W.M.K. Matsumura et al. / Geobios 48 (2015) 397–415
Gutie´ rrez and Archangelsky, 1997; Di Pasquo et al., 2009), South Africa (Plumstead, 1967; Anderson and Anderson, 1985), and Antarctica (Mildenhall and Schopf, 1980). Comparisons with previously described species permitted classifying them into four taxa: H. irregularis, H. furquei, H. baldisii and H. cf. kowensis. Morphometric analysis based on measured stem characters supports the taxonomic separation of the four analyzed species. H. cf. kowensis may represent a distinct part or even a juvenile stage of H. irregularis, but further analysis based on size and form of leaf cushion is needed to conﬁrm this hypothesis. H. furquei and H. baldisii are considered as two different morphospecies. Apparently, the oldest record of Haplostigma occurs in the Pircas Negras Formation, from the (?)Late Emsian of Argentina. After- wards, during the Givetian/Early Frasnian, the genus expanded to almost all high to middle latitude Gondwana terrains within the cool-temperate climate zone. As an endemic plant of Gondwana, Haplostigma appears to be an element restricted to, and consequently well adapted to mid-to-high latitudes and cold climatic regimes characteristic of the ASA Subrealm (Di Pasquo et al., 2009; Matsumura et al., 2014).
